					<p>From the marginal distribution for summer activities (the row totals), we find that <em>139</em> students plan to work this summer.  From the marginal distribution for class standing (the column totals), we see that <em>105</em> Juniors participated in the study.</p>
					<p>Note that the sum of the row totals and column totals should both add up to the grand total, which is 400 in this case.</p>
				</solution>
			</example>
			<p>A contingency table is a great tool for summarizing bivariate qualitative data. But in order to describe this data with a graph, we will need to make a modification to our bar graph. We will use a	special type of bar graph called a <term>stacked bar graph</term>.</p>
			<definition xml:id="def_stacked-bar-graph">
				<idx>stacked bar graph</idx>
				<idx><h>graphs</h><h>stacked bar graph</h></idx>
				<statement>
					<p>A <term>stacked bar graph</term> is used to display the data in a <xref ref="def_contingency-table" text="custom">contingency table</xref>. One of the two variables is chosen as the <term>primary variable</term>, and a bar is created for each category of the primary variable. The height of the bar is equal to the <xref ref="def_marginal-distribution" text="custom">marginal distribution</xref> entry for that category. The bar is broken up into <q>stacked</q> pieces, the heights of which represent the frequency of the <term>secondary variable</term> categories within that primary variable category.</p>
				</statement>
			</definition>
			<p>This definition can be difficult to decipher. Let&apos;s look at stacked bar graphs	for the summer plans data. Again, these graphs were created using a spreadsheet program.</p>
